      "content": "# KAP Codebook: Vaccine Confidence Study\n\n## KNOWLEDGE (K)\nUnderstanding and awareness of vaccine-related information\n\n### K1: Scientific Literacy\nParticipant demonstrates understanding of vaccine mechanisms, clinical evidence, or trial data. Includes references to understanding mRNA technology, trial phases, or data interpretation.\n- *Example*: \"I looked up the clinical trial data\" / \"understand vaccine safety data\"\n\n### K2: Information Exposure\nParticipant mentions sources where they encountered vaccine information (media, peers, providers, social platforms). Includes passive exposure and active seeking.\n- *Example*: \"I've read conflicting information online\" / \"social media is where I get most health info\"\n\n### K3: Knowledge Gaps\nParticipant expresses uncertainty, confusion, or missing information about vaccines. Includes explicit acknowledgment of not knowing or conflicting information.\n- *Example*: \"I don't know who to trust\" / \"I feel like we weren't getting the full picture\"\n\n---\n\n## ATTITUDES (A)\nBeliefs, emotions, and dispositions toward vaccines\n\n### A1: Trust/Distrust in Institutions\nParticipant expresses confidence or skepticism toward government, pharma, healthcare providers, or medical systems. Includes historical context (Tuskegee, etc.).\n- *Example*: \"I trust her completely\" / \"hard to forget Tuskegee\" / \"distrust pharmaceutical companies\"\n\n### A2: Risk Perception\nParticipant evaluates personal or family-level risk from vaccine side effects, disease, or unknown consequences. Includes worry about long-term effects or specific adverse events.\n- *Example*: \"worried about long-term effects\" / \"cousin had some side effects\" / \"fever for two days\"\n\n### A3: Emotional Drivers\nParticipant expresses emotions (fear, frustration, reassurance, confidence) influencing vaccine attitudes. Includes emotional language and tone.\n- *Example*: \"confusing\" / \"frustrating\" / \"felt informed and supported\" / \"compelling\" posts\n\n---\n\n## PRACTICES (P)\nBehaviors, decisions, and actions related to vaccination\n\n### P1: Vaccination Decision\nParticipant describes whether they got vaccinated, when, for whom, and decision reasoning (required, family, protection, etc.).\n- *Example*: \"I got vaccinated myself because my job required it\" / \"vaccinated my children\"\n\n### P2: Deliberation/Wait-and-See\nParticipant describes taking time to decide, seeking information before acting, or delaying vaccination. Includes decision-making processes.\n- *Example*: \"let me take time to decide\" / \"decided to wait and see\" / \"didn't have enough time to research\"\n\n### P3: Social Influence/Peer Sharing\nParticipant describes discussing vaccines with others, peer influence, community norms, or sharing information in social groups.\n- *Example*: \"my sister got vaccinated\" / \"friend group shares articles\" / \"people share concerns during meetings\"\n\n"
