cerpt 5 - Provider Advocacy & Recognition of Barriers\n- **K1** Scientific Literacy (understands vaccine safety data)\n- **A1** Trust/Distrust (recognizes distrust of pharma and government)\n- **A3** Emotional Drivers (frustration, empathy)\n- **P1** Vaccination Decision (got vaccinated early, encourages others)\n- **P3** Social Influence (patient communication, listening to concerns)\n\n**Theme Count**: K1(1), A1(1), A3(1), P1(1), P3(1)\n\n### Excerpt 6 - Delayed Decision via Waiting Strategy\n- **P2** Deliberation/Wait-and-See (waited to see outcomes)\n- **A2** Risk Perception (cousin's side effects confirmed hesitation)\n- **K3** Knowledge Gaps (didn't get full picture from official sources)\n- **P1** Vaccination Decision (eventually vaccinated for family protection)\n- **A3** Emotional Drivers (felt rushed, insufficient time)\n- **P3** Social Influence (family members' needs, cousin's experience)\n\n**Theme Count**: P2(1), A2(1), K3(1), P1(1), A3(1), P3(1)\n\n---\n\n## Theme Frequency Analysis\n\n| Code | Frequency | Percentage | Key Insights |\n|------|-----------|------------|--------------|\n| **P3** Social Influence/Peer Sharing | 7 | 17.5% | Most frequent theme\u2014vaccine decisions driven by peer/family experiences and community norms |\n| **A3** Emotional Drivers | 7 | 17.5% | Strong emotional component\u2014fear, reassurance, frustration shape confidence |\n| **K2** Information Exposure | 5 | 12.5% | Multiple sources (social media, providers, peers); consistency matters |\n| **A1** Trust/Distrust in Institutions | 5 | 12.5% | Institutional skepticism present; history matters (Tuskegee), provider relationships critical |\n| **P1** Vaccination Decision | 5 | 12.5% | Decision pathways varied (required, family, protection, deliberation) |\n| **P2** Deliberation/Wait-and-See | 5 | 12.5% | Time to decide valued; rushing perceived negatively; waiting for proof common |\n| **A2** Risk Perception | 4 | 10% | Anecdotal evidence (side effects) influences risk calculus more than statistics |\n| **K1** Scientific Literacy | 3 | 7.5% | When present, increases confidence; literacy gaps exacerbate information confusion |\n| **K3** Knowledge Gaps | 4 | 10% | Conflicting information and uncertainty common; need for clarity high |\n\n**Total Codes: 40**\n\n---\n\n## Key Behavioral Patterns\n\n1. **Trust Mediation** (A1, P3): Provider trust and peer social proof are strongest predictors of vaccine uptake\n2. **Information Quality Over Quantity** (K2, K3): Conflicting sources create paralysis; need curated, authoritative guidance\n3. **Emotional Primacy** (A3, A2): Risk perceptions driven by anecdotes and emotional resonance, not data\n4. **Deliberation Value** (P2): Rushed decisions resisted; offering time increases acceptance\n5. **Community Norms** (P3): Family and peer behavior influence decisions more than mass messaging\n\n"
